text: ¬†@Ahmed Mukhtar¬† Let's do a deep dive then. Why do you think Pakistan's economy worsened to the point that the common man got so agitated about prices of basic commodities? This agitation is what led to building up of the no-confidence motion. It's the same as what is happening in Sri Lanka. Surprisingly enough, China is able to persuade countries to take its loans despite their harsh lending policies. Under Shehbaz Sharif, this will continue to worsen as he is pro-China. He will be able to remain popular in Pakistan for 1 year by currying the favor of the Chinese but in the long run, Pakistan's economy is going to be demolished as a result. There are only 2 possible outcomes after that: Either Pakistan becomes a puppet of China or another political crisis (like Sri Lanka). In both cases, India needs to be wary. The first shall lead to Pakistan taking a more critical stance against India. The 2nd shall lead to a refugee crisis. Both of these will lead to increased insurgency. The best case scenario for both India and Paksitan was always a PM candidate like Imran Khan. The situation is too delicate for a change in leadership.
author: Aditya Chawla

text: ¬†@Aditya Chawla¬† Economy worsened because it's am import based economy and the previous government didn't focus on exports. even in your country inflation rose by 6% which is too high. Both countries have high inflation. That doesn't mean pak is becoming another srilanka. The no-confidence motion is a democratic process and it can happen at anytime. there's no need to call it "Crises". If you google you will see there has been 0 riots or killings and so far everything has been peaceful. I will say one thing tho, Imran khan should work on his diplomacy skills and not try to act so bold. He should also trade with the neighboring countries.
author: Ahmed Mukhtar

text: ¬†@Ahmed Mukhtar¬† I applaud the fact that army didn't throw their weight and the democratic values were upheld. I am not calling the no-confidence motion a crisis. But Pakistan is burying itself in its own loans. The BRI project yields 0 income to Pak until completed and Chinese govt offers no charity. Every infra they help build comes with a cost. It's a pattern that Indian news outlets have been hollering about since god knows when. Sri Lanka still ended up falling for it. There's no proof suggesting that Pakistan will end up any different, no matter how optimistic you try to be. I believe Pak can do better since the situation is more amenable but at the end of the day, the threat of Chinese "support" is too big to be ignored.

China needs pak due to the gawadar port and pak needs china due to their products that can be imported into pakistan. do you think you have another solution to this problem?
author: Ahmed Mukhtar

text:
‚Äã¬†@Ahmed Mukhtar¬† I don't know how American weapons ended up in Taliban's hands or how could Bin Laden be finding safe haven in Islamabad when USA was such a staunch ally of Pakistan. But you can't say that Pak didn't have a chance to form a strong alliance with the US. 

Even if we ignore the past, I can relate to your situation. China is to Pakistan what Russia is to India. But India has been diversifying its military alliances. We bought the Rafale from France and we are working on indigenous aircraft like the AMCA. The only way to save herself for Pak is to do exactly that. Invest in indigenous systems and form diplomatic relations with other countries which specialize in defense productions. If Pak continues to deal with China then it must be done very very carefully. Unfortunately, leaders are rarely ever educated enough to plan for that long in the future (I don't mean to insult Pak specifically, every country is like that). Another very simple alternative: Restructure BRI projects so that the self-serving Chinese don't get away with destroying Pak's economy. Let good sense prevail- Insist on approving BRI projects only if it comes with lower than ever interest rates and easy deadlines. Are you really okay with getting defense equipment in exchange for economic destruction?
